<div class="prose">
<p>
Popular music is often looked on with cynicism as insipid and endlessly recycled. Critics of the top 40 might suggest that the key to making a hit song is just to copy and paste an earlier success with some superficial variation. But recent research suggests that the opposite may be true. In their paper <a href="http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/0003122417728662">What Makes Popular Culture Popular? Product Features and Optimal Differentiation in Music</a>, professors Noah Askin and Michael Mauskapf analyzed 60 years worth of tracks from the Billboard Hot 100, and found that the songs that chart highest tend to be <i>less similar</i> to their predecessors than others. It pays to be different (though not <i>too</i> different).
</div>

<div id="story">

<div class="sticky"></div>

<div class="prose scrolltext" data-clearsong="1">
<p>
The authors analyzed the songs in their dataset using <i>sonic features</i> - that is, properties calculated from the raw audio of the songs.
</p>

<p class="step" data-song="Believe" data-hide_avg="1">
Let's go over some of those features. As an example, I'll be using <i>Believe</i> by Cher, which held the #1 spot on the Billboard Hot 100 for four weeks in 1999.
</p>

