<div> <!-- rap -->
<div class="step" data-song="In Da Club" data-highlight_sonics="speechiness">
<p>The golden age of hip hop may have been during the late 80's and early 90's, but it wasn't until the early 2000's that hip hop tracks began regularly hitting #1. Earlier examples were often novelties (<i>Baby Got Back</i>, <i>Ice Ice Baby</i>), or pop songs with rap elements (e.g. Paula Abdul's <i>Opposites Attract</i>, or Blondie's 1981 song <i>Rapture</i>, often cited as the first Billboard #1 to include rap).
</p>
<p class="step" data-highlight_sonics="speechiness">
Rapping often sounds a lot like spoken word, so rap songs tend to have a distinctively high speechiness score.
</p>

